Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel!). Pop the potato on a large #baking tray{} in a single layer. Drizzle with oil, then season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Toss to coat, then spread out and roast on the top shelf of your oven until golden, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking.

> Use two baking trays if necessary, you want the potatoes nicely spread out.

Meanwhile, halve the @baby plum tomatoes{125%g}. Peel and grate the @garlic{1%clove} (or use a #garlic press{}). Half, peel and chop the @red onion{1}(peeled and chopped into 2cm chunks). When the potatoes are halfway through cooking, add the onion and @dried oregano{1%(tsp)} to the tray, toss to coat and roast in your oven for the remaining time.

Pop the @panko breadcrumbs{10%g} into a #medium bowl{}. Add the @water{2%tbsp} and the @Baharat spice mix{1%(tbsp)}. Season with salt and pepper and mix together. Add the garlic and @lamb mince{200%g} and mix with your hands until combined. and shape into 4 sausage shapes per person. Flatten to make koftas and pop onto a #plate{}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands after handling raw meat.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on a medium high heat. When hot, add the koftas and cook turning frequently until browned all over and crisp, ~{8-10%minutes}.

> The lamb is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Pop the koftas onto a plate and cover with #foil{} to keep warm. Drain the fat from the pan and add half the @balsamic vinegar{24%ml} and all the @fig jam{40%g}, bring to a boil and remove from the heat. Add a splash of water if it needs it.

In a #small bowl{}, combine the @olive oil{1%tbsp} for the dressing, the remaining @balsamic vinegar{} and a pinch of salt. Pop the tomatoes and @wild rocket{40%g} in the bowl and mix well to dress.

Share the potatoes between your plates, place the salad and koftas alongside. Pour the balsamic fig sauce over the koftas and enjoy!